Assessment / Plan
OBESITY DISCUSSION:
The patient's weight was addressed. Weight loss, appropriate diet, and exercise were recommended. I also explained how excessive weight impacts the patient's musculoskeletal complaints.
TOTAL KNEE REPLACEMENT DISCUSSION:
The patient was made aware of the following treatment options for arthritis:
1. No treatment and continue to live with the pain, limitations, and/or disability of the injury.
2. Continue with non-operative treatment such as medicines, bracing, injections, or assistive devices.
3. Proceed with operative measures for joint replacement.
The procedure will consist of:
1. Removal of the diseased tissue, cartilage, and bone.
2. Reshaping the bone to accept the artificial implant.
3. Balancing the ligaments and soft tissues for optimal stability and function.
4. Implanting the joint replacement with or without cement.
The procedure will be performed on an inpatient basis. Length of stay varies based on health issues, strength, participation in therapy, and home support. Based on the patient's social situation, health, and insurance, inpatient rehab or home health care will be arranged by the social worker. The anesthesia will involve general anesthesia. A block may be performed or local anaesthetic added. The anesthesiologist will discuss the risks of anesthesia on the day of surgery.
Risks of the procedure include but are not limited to: infection, bleeding, blood transfusions, injury to a nerve or blood vessel, stiffness, instability, fracture, ligament or tendon damage, continued pain, continued disability, deep vein thrombosis (DVT), complications of a DVT, anesthesia complications, medical complications, painful or failed implant, loosening of the prosthesis, and need for future surgery.
The patient understood the risks and benefits of non-operative or surgical treatment, the operative and postoperative requirements, and the treatment alternatives. Knowing this, the patient wished to proceed with surgical intervention. My staff and I reviewed the procedures for surgery with the patient.
